/**
 * Long-form, beginner-friendly explanations for each glossary entry.
 * Shown in the expandable "Read more" panel under the short definition.
 *
 * Style rules:
 *   - Plain language. Spell acronyms out the first time.
 *   - No em dashes. Use periods, commas, or parentheses instead.
 *   - At least ~500 characters per entry.
 *   - Cover three things in plain order:
 *       1. What it really is, in everyday words.
 *       2. When you would pick it (and what you would pick instead).
 *       3. What to plan for: accessibility, mobile, scale, or pitfalls.
 *
 * Not every entry has to be encyclopedic. The goal is to help someone new
 * to "vibe coding" build the right mental picture before they ask an AI
 * tool to generate it.
 */

export const GLOSSARY_DETAILS = {
  // ─── Overlays (glossary.js) ──────────────────────────────────────────────
  modal:
    'A modal is a focused conversation. The page behind it usually dims (the dim layer is called the backdrop), and the keyboard cannot move into the page until the modal is closed. That is a strong promise to the user, so use a modal only when you really need a clear answer or completed action before they go on.\n\nGood fits include confirming a destructive action like deleting an account, signing in, or stepping through a short form. Skip it for things people might want to read alongside the page; a side panel or popover is gentler. When you ask for a modal, mention what closes it (Escape key, clicking the backdrop, a Cancel button), where focus should land when it opens, and where it should return when it closes.\n\nOn phones, modals often grow to full screen so make sure the close target is at least 44 by 44 pixels.',

  drawer:
    'A drawer slides in from the edge of the screen, usually the left or right, and overlays the content next to it. It is great when you need extra space for a related task without leaving the page. Common uses include a shopping cart preview, a comments side panel, the main mobile navigation, or filters next to a results list.\n\nCompared to a modal, a drawer is a little less demanding because the page is still visible behind it. Compared to a sidebar, a drawer is temporary instead of always there. When you describe a drawer, say which side it slides from, whether the page should still be clickable behind it, and how it closes (swipe, tap outside, Escape).\n\nOn small screens it often makes sense for the drawer to take the full width so people can read comfortably.',

  popover:
    'A popover is a small floating panel attached to a button or link. It usually points at the thing that opened it and closes when you click outside, press Escape, or focus moves away.\n\nUse a popover for short, related extras like a date picker, a profile menu, a small settings group, or hover help that needs to be interactive. It is lighter than a modal because the page underneath stays usable, and richer than a tooltip because it can hold inputs and links.\n\nWhen you ask for one, describe what triggers it, roughly where it should appear (above, below, start or end of the trigger), and whether it should follow the trigger when the page scrolls. Keep the content short; if you find yourself adding tabs, you probably want a modal or a real page.',

  tooltip:
    'A tooltip is a tiny label that appears when you hover or focus on something, usually to explain an icon or a shortened bit of text. It is for hints only, never for important information, because keyboard users will not see it unless focus is properly handled and touch users have no hover at all.\n\nReach for a tooltip when an icon button needs a name, a truncated cell needs its full value, or a small badge needs a sentence of context. If a control truly cannot work without the explanation, use a visible label instead.\n\nWhen you ask for tooltips, say how long to wait before showing one (200 to 500 milliseconds is normal), and remember to add an aria-label to icon-only buttons so screen readers also get the name.',

  toast:
    'A toast is a small message that appears at the edge of the screen, waits a few seconds, then disappears on its own. It is best for quick confirmations like "Saved", "Copied", or "Uploaded 3 files", and for non-blocking warnings such as "You are offline".\n\nAvoid using toasts for anything the user must read or act on, because they vanish and people miss them. For errors that need a fix, prefer an inline message near the offending field.\n\nWhen you specify a toast, mention how long it stays (4 to 6 seconds is friendly), where it appears (often top-right on desktop, bottom on mobile), and whether the user can pause or dismiss it. Set the live-region politeness so screen readers also announce it without interrupting whatever the user is doing.',

  select:
    'A select is a dropdown for picking one value from a known list. It is fine when there are only a handful of options that fit on one screen and the user already knows what they are choosing between, like Country, Language, or Status.\n\nAs lists grow past about ten items, plain selects become slow to scan. That is when you want a combobox instead, which adds a search box that filters as you type.\n\nA combobox is also the right choice when options come from a large or remote list, like users in a directory or products in a catalog. Either way, label the field clearly, support full keyboard use (Tab to focus, Arrow keys to move, Enter to choose, Escape to close), and remember that on mobile a native select often gives the best touch experience.',

  otp:
    'An OTP field, short for one-time password or one-time code, is a row of single-character boxes used for short verification codes that arrive by email or text message. Six digits is most common.\n\nThe boxes look intentional and signal "this is a temporary code, not a regular password". Auto-advance moves focus to the next box as the user types, and pasting the full code at once should fill every box.\n\nReach for this when confirming sign-in, recovering an account, or completing a payment step. Make sure mobile keyboards open as a numeric keypad, support paste for password managers, and provide a visible Resend code link with a clear cool-down so people are not stuck if the message never arrived.',

  switch:
    'A switch is a small lever that toggles a setting on or off. It is ideal for things that take effect right away, like turning on dark mode, enabling notifications, or pausing email digests.\n\nThe change should be obvious without pressing Save. If the choice instead picks one option from a list (Small, Medium, Large), use a segmented control or radio group; switches are only for true on or off.\n\nPair a switch with a clear label so the meaning is not buried in design alone, and announce state changes to screen readers using the standard switch role. On touch devices the hit target should be at least 44 pixels tall, and the visual difference between on and off should not rely on color alone (add a position change or an icon).',

  dropzone:
    'A dropzone is a target area where you can drag and drop files, or click to open the system file picker. It is friendlier than a bare file input because it shows people where the file should go and gives clear feedback when they drag a file over it. Use it when uploads are a key part of the screen: profile pictures, documents, importing data, or attaching media to a post.\n\nAlways include the click-to-browse fallback because keyboard users cannot drag and drop. Show accepted file types and the maximum size in plain words, and reflect the same limits in the underlying input attributes. Once a file is selected, show the file name, size, an inline progress bar, and a way to remove or retry.\n\nFor bulk uploads, list each file as its own row so errors are easy to spot.',

  radio:
    'A radio group is a set of choices where exactly one item can be selected at a time, like picking a payment method or a shipping speed. The visual is usually a row of small circles, each next to a label, but radios styled as cards (with bigger hit areas, icons, or descriptions) are common when the choices need more explaining.\n\nUse radios when you want every option visible at once so people can compare them. If there are more than about seven options, switch to a select or combobox so the page does not get crowded.\n\nWrap radios in a fieldset with a legend so screen readers announce the question, and let arrow keys move between options the way the platform expects.',

  slider:
    'A slider lets users pick a number by dragging a handle along a track. It works well for ranges that make sense visually, like volume, brightness, price filters, or zoom.\n\nSliders are quick for rough values but precise typing is hard, so include a number field next to the slider when accuracy matters (budget, dates, ages). Show the current value clearly, mark the minimum and maximum, and add tick marks if values snap to a step.\n\nSupport keyboard use with Arrow keys for small steps, Page Up and Page Down for larger jumps, and Home and End for the ends of the range. On touch screens, give the handle plenty of padding so a fingertip can grab it without the user having to be careful.',

  table:
    'A data table arranges records in rows and columns so people can compare values across many items at once. Reach for a table when the data has clear fields (name, status, owner, date) and users need to scan, sort, or filter.\n\nFor lighter content where each row needs more visual variety, a list or card grid is a better fit. Plan for the parts that make tables actually useful: column sorting with a visible direction indicator, sticky header so labels stay visible while scrolling, optional sticky first column on wide tables, pagination or virtualized rows when the dataset is large, and a clear empty state when there are no results.\n\nOn phones, do not just shrink columns; consider stacking each row into a card layout instead.',

  list:
    'A list shows items one after another, top to bottom. It is the right choice when each item has roughly the same shape (an avatar, a title, maybe a status) and people are scanning rather than comparing across columns. Use lists for chat conversations, notification feeds, search results, or settings groups.\n\nIf users need to compare many fields side by side, switch to a table. If items are visually rich and roughly the same size, consider a card grid. Make the whole row clickable when there is one obvious action, show a clear hover and focus state, and design the empty state so the screen still feels intentional when there is nothing to show.\n\nOn mobile, large rows with comfortable padding are easier to tap than dense ones.',

  carousel:
    'A carousel rotates through a few items in the same slot, often with arrows and dots so people can move forward or back. It can save space for hero promotions, testimonials, or a small set of featured products.\n\nThe risk is that anything past the first slide gets very few views, and auto-rotation can be frustrating for people using screen readers or who need extra time to read. If you do use one, prefer manual controls over auto-play, pause on hover and on focus, support swipe on touch, and announce slide changes politely.\n\nFor long lists, consider a horizontally scrolling row with snap points instead; it shows progress naturally and lets people scroll at their own pace.',

  tree:
    'A tree is a list of items that nest inside each other. It is perfect for file folders, category drilldowns, organization charts, and JSON-like data.\n\nEach branch can expand to reveal its children with a small arrow, and clicking the arrow should not also select the row. Use a tree when the data is genuinely hierarchical and people need to see the structure; a flat list is simpler when relationships do not matter.\n\nSupport keyboard use the way operating systems do: Right arrow to expand, Left arrow to collapse, Up and Down arrows to move, Enter to act on the focused item. For very large trees, only render the visible nodes (lazy load children) and persist which branches were open so the view does not reset when the user comes back.',

  calendar:
    'A calendar shows days laid out in a month grid. It is the inside view of a date picker and also a standalone surface for scheduling, attendance, or events.\n\nUse it when seeing days in context matters (weekends, the shape of a month, a meeting that spans several days). For just picking a single date in a form, a smaller date input or popover calendar is enough.\n\nFor a custom calendar, label weekdays clearly, mark today with both color and an outline so it is visible to color-blind users, and make sure keyboard users can move day by day with arrows, jump weeks with Page Up and Page Down, and confirm with Enter. Respect the locale for first day of the week and date format.',

  statcard:
    'A stat card (sometimes called a KPI card or metric tile) shows one number prominently with a short label and often a small change indicator like "up 12 percent versus last week". It is the building block of dashboards.\n\nUse stat cards for the few measures that matter most, not as a wall of every number you have. Keep the label short, the unit obvious, and the comparison meaningful (versus last period, versus goal).\n\nColor the change with care: green for good and red for bad assumes a context (revenue good, errors bad), so add an arrow or a plus and minus sign too. Make the whole card a link when the next step is to drill into a detailed report.',

  datepicker:
    'A date picker is a small calendar that opens from a text field so users can pick a single day. It is the right tool for due dates, birthdays, appointments, and reservation single-night stays.\n\nFor picking a start and end day at once, use a date range picker; for picking a clock time, pair it with a separate time picker. Always allow typing in the field as a fallback because typing is faster for confident users, and parse common formats (slashes, dashes, two or four digit years).\n\nShow the locale-correct format hint near the field, disable invalid days visually and programmatically, and on mobile lean on the native date input where possible since it brings the platform keyboard.',

  command:
    'A command palette is a searchable menu of actions and places, opened with a keyboard shortcut (Command-K on Mac, Control-K on Windows). Typing narrows the list so people do not have to dig through menus to find what they want.\n\nIt is a power-user pattern that fits apps with many features (editors, dashboards, design tools), and it can serve a beginner well too if it suggests next steps. Group commands by area, show the keyboard shortcut next to each one, and support keyboard navigation throughout (Arrow keys to move, Enter to run, Escape to close).\n\nShow recently used commands first so the palette gets faster the more it is used. Make sure search ignores accents and small typos so it is forgiving.',

  taginput:
    'A tag input lets people enter several short labels into one field, with each label shown as a small removable chip. Common uses include adding email recipients, choosing topics for a post, or tagging photos.\n\nPeople can usually press Enter or comma to commit a tag, Backspace to remove the last one, and click the small X on a chip to remove it. If your tags should be picked from a known list, prefer a multi-select combobox so users do not invent typos; if the list is open-ended, a tag input is the right call.\n\nValidate as you type (no duplicates, accepted format), keep keyboard focus inside the field while editing, and announce when chips are added or removed so assistive tech keeps up.',

  richtext:
    'A rich text editor lets users format content as they write, with controls for bold, italic, lists, links, headings, and sometimes images or tables. It is the right tool for blog posts, comments with formatting, internal docs, and support replies.\n\nThere are two common output formats: HTML (matches what you see) and Markdown (a simple text format that can be re-rendered later). Pick one and tell the AI which you want, because the choices behind the scenes (sanitization, copy and paste handling) are different.\n\nKeep the toolbar short by default and add an overflow menu for advanced controls. Support keyboard shortcuts (Command-B for bold, etc.), paste cleanup so styles from other apps do not pollute the page, and make sure the editor area itself is keyboard reachable like a normal text field.',

  rating:
    'A rating shows a score, usually as five stars, that users can either read (display only) or set (interactive). Use it on reviews, surveys, and feedback prompts.\n\nStars work because the scale is familiar, but include a number and total nearby (for example "4.3 out of 5, 218 reviews") so the meaning is clear without color. Allow half-star ratings only if your data really supports them; otherwise integers are easier to interpret.\n\nFor input, support keyboard use with Arrow keys to change the value, and announce the current selection to screen readers. Consider a separate text comment field for context, since a single number rarely tells the full story.',

  stepper:
    'A stepper guides users through a multi-step task by breaking it into clear steps with a progress indicator at the top. It is great when each step is meaningful on its own (account, address, payment, review) and skipping ahead would be confusing. Show step names, the current step, completed steps, and any optional steps.\n\nAllow going back without losing data, and validate each step as the user leaves it so errors are caught early. For very short flows (two or three small fields), a single page is friendlier. For long flows, save progress automatically so people can come back later.\n\nOn mobile, a horizontal stepper can become tiny; consider stacking step labels vertically or hiding labels behind the active step.',

  sidebar:
    'A sidebar is a vertical column on the side of the page that holds primary navigation or filters. It is great for apps with many sections because it stays in one place and acts as a map of the product.\n\nReach for a collapsible variant on smaller screens so it can shrink to icons or hide entirely, and a drawer version on phones because there is no room to keep it open. Group items into clearly labeled sections, mark the active item visually, and keep the labels short.\n\nSupport keyboard navigation (Tab to move, Enter to activate) and remember the user expanded or collapsed state across visits. If your app only has three or four destinations, a top navigation bar is usually simpler.',

  card:
    'A card is a small container that groups related content (image, title, description, action) so it reads as one thing. Cards are the workhorse of grids: product listings, blog teasers, dashboards, and search results all use them.\n\nThey are most powerful when each card has the same shape so the page is easy to scan. Make the whole card clickable when there is one obvious primary action, and avoid putting more than one or two interactive controls inside (otherwise it gets confusing about what clicking the card does).\n\nKeep the corner radius and padding consistent across the app, support hover and focus states, and design how cards collapse on small screens (often into a single column).',

  masonry:
    'A masonry layout arranges items in columns and lets each item keep its own height, so the result looks like a brick wall with no awkward gaps. It is a strong fit for image galleries, Pinterest-style boards, and feeds where items vary in size.\n\nUse a regular grid when you want all items to feel equal in importance, and a list when reading order matters. Be careful about reading order in masonry: visually columns flow top to bottom, but screen reader and keyboard order is still source order, so make sure that order matches your content.\n\nLazy-load images and reserve space for them with width and height attributes so the layout does not jump as content arrives.',

  tabs:
    'Tabs let people switch between two or three views of the same area without leaving the page, like Overview and Activity on a profile, or Code and Preview on a snippet. Use tabs when the content really is parallel, peer to peer; if one section is a drilldown of another, it is a link or accordion instead.\n\nShow a clear active state with both color and an underline or background, support keyboard navigation (Left and Right arrows to move, Home and End to jump), and update the page URL with the active tab where possible so the view can be linked and refreshed. Keep tab labels short (one or two words).\n\nWhen there are too many to fit, switch to a dropdown or move to a sidebar.',

  breadcrumbs:
    'Breadcrumbs are a horizontal trail of links that show where the current page sits inside a hierarchy, like Home > Docs > Components > Button. They help people understand structure and jump back up several levels in one click.\n\nThey make sense in deep apps and content sites with real nesting (file managers, e-commerce categories, documentation). They are unnecessary in flat apps with a clear top navigation.\n\nUse a small separator that is easy to read (a slash or a chevron) and make every step a real link except the current page, which should be plain text. On small screens, consider collapsing the middle of long trails into a menu so the start and end are still visible.',

  accordion:
    'An accordion is a list of headers, each of which expands to show its details. It is great for FAQs, settings groups, and long forms where most of the page would otherwise be content the user does not need at once.\n\nPick whether only one section can be open at a time (good for FAQs) or any number can be open (good for settings). Use a clear icon (often a chevron) that rotates to show open or closed, and animate the expand and collapse so the change is easy to follow.\n\nMake headers full-width buttons so the whole row is clickable, support keyboard activation (Enter and Space), and let assistive tech announce expanded or collapsed state.',

  contextmenu:
    'A context menu opens at the cursor when you right-click (or long-press on touch). It lists actions specific to whatever you clicked: a row, a file, a piece of text.\n\nIt is great for power users in dense apps because it puts options where the cursor already is, but it must never be the only way to reach an action because right-click is invisible to most people. Always offer the same options elsewhere (a button, a more menu, a top toolbar).\n\nSupport keyboard use too: open with the menu key or Shift-F10, navigate with Arrow keys, run with Enter, close with Escape. Group related items with separators, show shortcut hints next to actions, and keep the list short.',

  dragdrop:
    'Drag and drop lets users move items by clicking, holding, and dragging them to a new place. It is intuitive for reordering lists, moving cards between columns on a kanban board, and uploading files.\n\nThe risk is that dragging is not accessible by default; keyboard users and screen reader users need an alternative. That can be Up and Down buttons next to each item, a small menu that says "Move to top" or "Move to column X", or a numeric position field.\n\nWhile dragging, show a clear placeholder where the item will land, scroll the container if the user drags near the edge, and animate the drop so the change is easy to follow. Always announce the result to assistive tech.',

  lightbox:
    'A lightbox opens an image (or video) at a larger size on top of a dimmed page. It is the standard way to show a photo gallery without taking the user to a separate page.\n\nFit-to-window vs zoom, swipe between images, keyboard arrows to navigate, and Escape to close are the basic moves. Keep the close button big and obvious, position arrows where thumbs can reach them on mobile, and preload the next and previous images so navigation feels instant.\n\nTrap focus inside the lightbox while it is open and return focus to the thumbnail that opened it on close. For pinch-zoom on touch, make sure the page itself does not scroll under the lightbox.',

  infinitescroll:
    'Infinite scroll loads more items as the user nears the bottom of the list, instead of using numbered pages. It can feel magical for feeds (social posts, search results, photo grids) where there is no natural stopping point.\n\nThe trade-offs are real: footers become unreachable, jumping back to a specific spot is hard, and screen readers can get lost. Always offer a manual "Load more" button as a fallback, show a clear loading state at the bottom, and stop loading when there are no more items with a friendly end marker.\n\nFor very long sessions consider numbered pagination as a shortcut, and persist scroll position when the user comes back to the page.',

  alert:
    'An alert is an inline message inside the page (not a popup) that explains something the user should know: a warning, an error, a success confirmation, or general info. Use a recognizable icon plus a short title and one or two sentences of clear next steps.\n\nColor helps but should not be the only signal, since color-blind users may not see the difference. Pair severity with the right ARIA live region (polite for informational, assertive only for errors that need immediate attention) so screen readers announce them correctly.\n\nIf the alert is dismissible, place the close button consistently and keep the spacing comfortable for touch. Avoid stacking multiple alerts; group similar messages together when you can.',

  empty:
    'An empty state is the screen you see when there is nothing to show: no search results, no items yet, no notifications. A good empty state explains why the area is empty in plain words, suggests the next step, and (when relevant) gives a primary action button to take it.\n\nTreat empty states as opportunities to teach people what the feature does, not as bugs to hide. Use a small illustration or icon, but keep the text in front.\n\nConsider three flavors: first-time empty (you have not added anything yet), filtered empty (no results match these filters, with a Clear filters action), and error empty (something went wrong, with a Retry).',

  badge:
    'A badge is a small label, usually rounded, that adds extra meta information next to text or an icon. Common uses include status (Draft, Published, Failed), counts (3 unread), or tags (New, Beta, Pro). Keep them short, ideally one word or a small number, and do not put many in one row.\n\nFor counts above a threshold show "99+" rather than huge numbers. Color helps but is not enough on its own; pair the color with text or a small icon so meaning survives in grayscale and for color-blind users. Place the badge somewhere consistent (always after the title, always top-right of the icon) so people learn where to look.\n\nMake sure the badge text is readable at small sizes.',

  avatars:
    'An avatar group shows several user pictures stacked or in a row, often used to represent participants in a meeting, members of a project, or people who reacted to a post. Limit how many you show (often three to five) and add a "+N" chip for the rest.\n\nKeep the visual order stable so the same person is in the same position over time. Provide alt text or a tooltip with each person name for screen readers, since just an image is not enough.\n\nWhen stacking with overlap, make sure each circle has a clear ring around it so they are visually separate even on busy backgrounds. On click, show the full list in a popover or modal.',

  timeline:
    'A timeline lays out events in chronological order along a line. It is great for activity history, project milestones, order tracking, and onboarding progress.\n\nEach event usually has a date or time, an icon or marker, a title, and a short description. Use a vertical layout for variable-length descriptions and a horizontal one when each step is short and equal.\n\nGroup events by day or week when there are many, and let users collapse older sections to keep the page readable. For accessibility, use a real ordered list under the hood so the sequence is clear to assistive tech, and announce dynamic additions politely.',

  skeleton:
    'A skeleton screen shows gray placeholder shapes in roughly the same layout as the real content, while the data is loading. It feels faster than a spinner because users can already see what is coming. Use skeletons for content-heavy screens (lists, cards, articles) where structure is predictable.\n\nFor tiny areas or unknown shapes, a small spinner is fine. Match the skeleton shapes closely to the real content so the page does not jump when data arrives. Keep the animation gentle (a slow shimmer) and make sure to remove skeletons promptly; lingering skeletons feel buggy.\n\nAlways pair them with a real timeout fallback so users see an error rather than waiting forever.',

  progress:
    'A progress bar shows how far along a task is when you can measure it: a file upload, a multi-step form, a long export. Use it when you can give a real percent or step count.\n\nIf you cannot, use a spinner instead. Show both the bar and a number (or step indicator) so people can see exact progress, and add a brief text label about what is happening ("Uploading 3 of 5 files").\n\nEstimated times can help on slow tasks, but only if the estimate is reasonably accurate, otherwise it is more frustrating than no estimate. Make the bar tall enough to see and contrast strongly with its background, and respect reduced-motion preferences.',

  hero:
    'A hero section is the big visual block at the top of a marketing or landing page. It usually contains a one-line headline, a short subheadline, a primary call-to-action button, and a supporting image, video, or animation.\n\nIts job is to set the value proposition fast: who this product is for, what it does, and what to do next. Keep the copy short and specific; avoid vague slogans.\n\nUse only one primary action button, with maybe one secondary link next to it. Make sure the design works with different headline lengths in different languages, that text is readable on the background image, and that the section does not push core content too far down on small screens.',

  pricing:
    'A pricing section presents your plans side by side so people can compare and pick one. Common patterns include a monthly vs annual toggle, a recommended plan highlighted in the middle, and a small features matrix below.\n\nBe honest about what is included and what is not, label limits in plain words, and show prices in the currency of the user when possible. Place the most common plan in the middle and emphasize it visually, but do not make other plans hard to read.\n\nInclude a clear next step on every plan (Start trial, Contact sales) and link to a more detailed comparison page if your feature list is long. For mobile, stack plans vertically and put the recommended plan first.',

  testimonial:
    'A testimonial section quotes real customers to build trust. Each card usually has a short quote, a name, a job title, and the company name (and ideally a photo or logo).\n\nUse direct quotes you actually have permission to publish, not stock copy. Keep quotes short; the most powerful ones are one or two sentences with a specific outcome ("Saved us four hours a week").\n\nFor a row of testimonials, design for varying lengths so cards do not look broken when one is longer. Add aria-label or a heading so the section is identifiable to screen readers, and make sure photos have meaningful alt text (the name of the person, not just "photo").',

  faq:
    'A frequently-asked-questions section is a list of common questions with answers, usually in an accordion so the page stays scannable. Use it for objections, edge cases, and topics that come up in support but do not deserve a full page on their own.\n\nOrder questions by importance, write the question in the user voice, and keep answers short and concrete. If an answer needs more depth, link to a detailed page.\n\nGroup long FAQ pages into clear categories (Pricing, Security, Billing) and add a search box if there are more than about a dozen items. Mark the answer container as a region with a label so screen reader users can navigate quickly.',

  pagination:
    'Pagination splits a long list into numbered pages with controls to move between them. It is the dependable alternative to infinite scroll: people can jump to a specific page, the URL describes their position so links work, and the footer is always reachable.\n\nUse it for tables, search results, and any list where browsing back to a specific item matters. Show the current page clearly, include First and Last buttons for very long sequences, and pick a page size that fits one screen comfortably (often 10, 25, or 50 rows).\n\nAdd a "Showing 21 to 30 of 248" hint for context, and on small screens collapse middle page numbers into an ellipsis to save space.',

  dropdownmenu:
    'A dropdown menu is a small button (often labeled "More" or shown as three dots) that opens a list of actions. It is great for grouping related actions next to a row, a card, or a header so the interface stays uncluttered.\n\nKeep menus short; if you have more than seven items, group them with separators or move some into the main interface. Show keyboard shortcuts next to actions where they exist, mark destructive actions with a different color and put them at the bottom, and make sure the menu can be operated entirely from the keyboard (Enter or Space to open, Arrow keys to move, Enter to select, Escape to close).',

  appshell:
    'An app shell is the outer frame of a web application: top bar, sidebar, footer, and the main content area in the middle. The shell stays roughly the same as users move from page to page, while only the content inside changes.\n\nDesigning the shell first is a good move because every screen in the app has to fit inside it. Decide where global controls live (search, notifications, user menu), how the layout adapts to mobile (sidebar collapses to a drawer), and how content scrolls (just the main area, or the whole page).\n\nPre-paint the shell quickly on first load so the app feels fast even before the data is there.',

  filterbar:
    'A filter bar is a strip of controls (selects, search, chips, date ranges) placed above a list or table to narrow the results. It is one of the highest-impact patterns for any app with lots of data.\n\nShow only the most common filters by default and tuck advanced ones behind an "All filters" button so the bar does not get crowded. Display the active filters as removable chips below the bar so people can see what is on, and include a Clear all button.\n\nSync the filter state with the URL so links and back buttons work, and remember a person last used filters when they return. On mobile, collapse the bar into a single Filters button that opens a drawer.',

  barchart:
    'A bar chart compares categories using rectangle lengths. It is the safest chart choice when you want to compare a handful of distinct things (sales by product, errors by service).\n\nUse vertical bars for short labels and horizontal bars for long labels (because labels read naturally on the left). Sort bars by value when ranking matters, or keep them in a meaningful order (months, steps) when sequence matters.\n\nAlways include axis labels with units, a clean baseline at zero (truncating the axis exaggerates differences), and a text summary or table for screen reader users. For comparing across two dimensions, group bars or stack them, but keep groups small (three or four) so the chart stays readable.',

  // ─── Batch 2 (glossaryBatch2.js) ─────────────────────────────────────────
  spinner:
    'A spinner is a small animated indicator that says "something is happening, please wait" without telling you exactly how much longer. It is the right choice when you cannot measure progress, such as a quick API call, signing in, or rendering a chart.\n\nIf you can measure progress, prefer a progress bar so users can see how far they have to go; if you can show the eventual layout, prefer a skeleton screen. Always pair a spinner with a short label like "Loading…" or "Saving…" so screen readers also understand what is happening, and add aria-busy so assistive tech ignores stale content.\n\nRespect the reduced-motion preference by swapping the spin for a gentler pulse, and remember to remove the spinner promptly once the work is done.',

  linechart:
    'A line chart connects data points with a line so people can see the shape of change over time. It is best for trends (visits per day, temperature over a week, response time over a month), where the order along the bottom axis is meaningful.\n\nUse a bar chart instead when comparing distinct categories, and an area chart when you want to emphasize total volume under the line. Label both axes with units (percent, dollars, milliseconds), include a date format and timezone where relevant, and keep grid lines light so the data stands out.\n\nFor more than one line, use distinct colors plus another distinguishing feature (dashes, point shapes) so color-blind readers can still tell them apart, and provide a text summary or data table for screen readers.',

  piechart:
    'A pie or donut chart shows how parts add up to a whole, like the share of revenue from each region. A donut is a pie with a hole in the middle, often used to show the total in the center.\n\nPie charts are easy to misuse; the human eye is bad at comparing the size of slices, especially small ones. Limit yourself to about six slices and group the rest into an "Other" bucket.\n\nShow percentages or values directly on each slice (or with leader lines) so values are not color-only, and include a text legend. If the goal is precise comparison, a bar chart is almost always clearer; pies are best when the story is "this one is the majority".',

  multiselect:
    'A multi-select lets users pick more than one option from a list, usually shown as removable chips below the field or checkmarks in the dropdown. It is the right choice when more than one answer is valid, like assigning tags to a post, choosing recipients for an email, or filtering a table by several statuses at once.\n\nIf only one answer is allowed, use a regular select. If users may need to type new options that are not in the list, use a tag input.\n\nShow how many items are selected, support a "Select all" or "Clear" action when the list is short, and announce selection changes politely so screen readers keep up. On mobile, consider a full-screen sheet for selecting from a long list.',

  daterange:
    'A date range picker captures a start day and an end day in one control. It is the standard for analytics filters ("Last 7 days", "This month") and for booking flows where the start and end belong together.\n\nProvide common presets so people do not have to click many times to set a typical range, and validate that the end is not before the start. Be explicit about the timezone of the stored values, especially when filters affect a global team.\n\nOn small screens, show one calendar at a time instead of two side by side. Support keyboard use (Arrow keys to move days, Page Up and Page Down for months, Enter to confirm) and show the chosen range as plain text alongside the calendar.',

  timepicker:
    'A time picker chooses a clock time, on its own or paired with a date. Make the format obvious: "2:30 PM" (12-hour) or "14:30" (24-hour) is a real source of confusion if not labeled.\n\nPick a sensible minute step (5, 15, or 30 minutes is common) and document it. For events that cross midnight or daylight-saving boundaries, pair the time with a date to avoid ambiguity.\n\nProvide arrow keys for stepping through hours and minutes from the keyboard, and keep an underlying machine-readable value (like an ISO datetime) for forms. On mobile, the native time input often gives the best touch experience and accessibility for free.',

  colorpicker:
    'A color picker lets users choose a color value. Common pieces include a hue slider, a saturation and lightness area, a hex code field (the six-character format like #6366f1), preset swatches, and sometimes an alpha slider for transparency.\n\nUse it in design tools, branding settings, theme editors, and chart customizations. Validate the hex input as you type and show a preview swatch so the result is obvious.\n\nIf your product has a brand palette, lead with those swatches as presets so users land on accessible color combinations. For more advanced uses, an eyedropper (sampling a color from anywhere on screen) is a delightful extra where the browser supports it.',

  combobox:
    'A combobox blends a text input with a dropdown list. As the user types, the list filters, but they still pick a real option from it.\n\nIt is the right choice when the list of valid options is too long to scan as a plain select, or when the options come from a server (people, products, places). It is not a general search box; the result is one chosen value, not a search query.\n\nFor asynchronous lookups, debounce keystrokes (wait a moment after typing stops before sending the request), cancel older requests, and show clear loading, empty, and error states. Follow the standard combobox keyboard pattern so screen readers and power users know what to expect.',

  inputgroup:
    'An input group is a text field with attached pieces called addons, like a leading "https://" prefix, a currency symbol on the left, or a Search button on the right. Use it when the addon helps clarify the field meaning or offers a single related action.\n\nKeep tab order natural (input first, then any trailing button) and make sure the addons line up visually with the input height. Avoid stuffing more than one addon on each side; if there is more, you probably want a separate field or a small toolbar.\n\nFor right-to-left languages, addons should swap sides automatically. Give the field a real label above (or visibly hidden) so screen readers do not just announce the prefix.',

  textfield:
    'A text field is the basic single-line input where people type short text: a name, an email, a search term. Always pair it with a visible label above so it stays readable when the field is filled and so screen readers can announce it.\n\nChoose the right input type (email, tel, url, number) so mobile keyboards adapt, validation hints appear, and password managers behave. Include a placeholder only as a hint, never as the only label, because it disappears when typing starts.\n\nShow errors inline below the field with both color and text, support clear visual focus, and keep the height tall enough to be comfortable on touch screens (about 44 pixels minimum).',

  passwordfield:
    'A password field hides what the user types behind dots so people behind them cannot read it. Add a visible "show password" toggle so users can verify what they typed; mistakes in long random strings are the leading cause of failed sign-ins.\n\nShow password requirements up front (minimum length, character classes) instead of revealing them only after a failure. Consider a strength meter for new passwords, but do not block reasonable choices on subjective scores.\n\nAlways allow paste, since password managers depend on it, and use the right autocomplete attribute (current-password vs new-password) so browsers help instead of getting in the way.',

  splitpane:
    'A split pane shows two or more panels side by side with a draggable divider between them. Common uses include code on the left and live preview on the right, a file tree next to a text editor, or two documents being compared.\n\nSet a minimum size for each panel so neither can collapse to nothing, and remember the user position across visits. Provide keyboard ways to resize (often the divider itself is a separator role with Arrow keys).\n\nOn smaller screens, switch to a stacked layout (top and bottom) or a tabbed view because two narrow columns are hard to read. Save the orientation and sizes per user so the layout persists.',

  menubar:
    'A menubar is a horizontal row of menus across the top of a window: File, Edit, View, Help. It is the desktop convention used in operating systems and full-featured apps.\n\nUse it when you have many actions that group naturally and you expect power users to learn the structure. For lighter web apps, a top navigation bar with a few links is enough, and a command palette or a more menu often replaces a menubar entirely.\n\nSupport full keyboard navigation (Arrow keys move within and between menus, Enter activates, Escape closes) and show shortcut hints next to actions. Keep top-level labels short so they fit even in localized languages.',

  megamenu:
    'A megamenu is a wide dropdown that opens from a top navigation item and shows columns of grouped links, sometimes with images or featured content. It works well for sites with many sections (large e-commerce stores, documentation portals) where a flat menu would be too long.\n\nMake sure it opens on click as well as on hover so keyboard and touch users can reach it, close it on Escape and on outside click, and keep the layout responsive: on smaller screens it usually collapses into a stacked accordion menu inside a drawer. Group items with clear headings, keep link labels short and predictable, and avoid hiding the only path to a page behind a megamenu category.',

  bottomnav:
    'A bottom navigation bar is a row of three to five primary destinations docked at the bottom of the screen. It is a mobile pattern because thumbs reach the bottom more easily than the top.\n\nUse it for the most important sections of an app (Home, Search, Inbox, Profile), keep labels short, and pair an icon with text so meaning is obvious. Mark the active destination clearly with both color and shape, and never put more than five items there because the labels become unreadable.\n\nOn larger screens, replace it with a sidebar or a top navigation bar; bottom navigation is awkward on desktop where the cursor is at the top.',

  segmented:
    'A segmented control is a small group of two to five mutually exclusive buttons joined together, like Day / Week / Month or List / Grid. It is great for switching the same data between a few views, with all options visible at once.\n\nIf you have more than five options, switch to a select; if multiple options can be on, use a row of toggle buttons instead. Highlight the active segment clearly with both background and text color, and support keyboard navigation (Left and Right arrows to move, Enter to confirm).\n\nOn small screens, segmented controls scale down well as long as labels stay readable; consider icons-only with tooltips when space is tight.',

  virtuallist:
    'A virtualized list only renders the rows currently visible on screen, then swaps them in and out as the user scrolls. The browser stays fast even with tens of thousands of rows because there are never more than a few dozen real elements at once.\n\nUse it for chat histories, long file tables, search results, and any infinite-scroll-like feed. Tell the AI tool which library to use (react-window and TanStack Virtual are popular) and whether rows have fixed or variable height; variable height needs a measure step.\n\nThe trade-off is that browser find-in-page only finds visible rows, and screen readers may announce the rendered subset, so include alternative ways to search and a clear total count.',

  chatthread:
    'A chat thread is a vertical scrolling conversation made of message bubbles, usually grouped by sender with timestamps and avatars. Use it for messaging products, support chat, and chat-like AI interfaces.\n\nKeep your own messages aligned to one side and the other person on the other side, and group consecutive messages from the same sender so the avatar does not repeat. Decide how Enter behaves in the composer (send or new line) and document it; a hint near the input goes a long way.\n\nShow typing and read indicators when relevant, scroll to the latest message on new arrivals (unless the user has scrolled up to read history), and announce new messages politely to screen readers.',

  notificationcenter:
    'A notification center is a persistent list of past notifications, often opened from a bell icon in the top bar. It complements toasts: toasts are quick and disappear, the center is where past messages live so people can review them later.\n\nGroup notifications by recency or category, mark which are unread, and let users mark all as read or jump to the source. Empty state matters: a friendly "You are all caught up" beats a blank panel.\n\nSync read state across devices so a user does not see the same unread count after dismissing it elsewhere, and respect notification-frequency preferences so the bell does not become noise.',

  codeblock:
    'A code block displays code with a monospace font, line numbers, and syntax highlighting so it is easy to read. Use it inline in documentation, blog posts, and developer tools.\n\nAlways include a Copy button (and confirm with a quick "Copied" state), let users select text without selecting line numbers, and label the language so syntax highlighters and screen readers know what they are showing. For long blocks, support horizontal scroll instead of breaking lines mid-syntax, and consider a "Wrap lines" toggle when copy fidelity matters less than reading.\n\nPick a high-contrast color theme and provide both light and dark variants.',

  mediaplayer:
    'A media player is the set of controls for video and audio: play and pause, seek bar, volume, fullscreen, and often captions and playback rate. Use the native HTML video and audio elements when you can; they bring keyboard support, captions, and accessibility features for free.\n\nFor richer needs (DRM, adaptive streaming), use a library like Video.js or Plyr. Keep the controls visible by default so people can find them, support keyboard shortcuts (Space to play and pause, Arrows to seek and adjust volume), and always provide captions for video and a transcript for audio.\n\nRespect autoplay rules: most browsers block sound, and many users find autoplay rude even where it works.',

  mapview:
    'A map view shows an interactive map you can pan and zoom. It is the right choice when location is the primary axis: store finders, ride-sharing, real-estate, delivery tracking.\n\nBe explicit about the provider you want (Mapbox, Google Maps, Leaflet with OpenStreetMap tiles, Apple MapKit) because pricing, attribution, and style vary. Add markers for items, cluster them when there are many, and offer a parallel list view so screen readers and people who prefer text can still browse results.\n\nBe careful with location permissions: ask only when needed, explain why, and default the view to a sensible region until permission is granted.',

  shortcutkeys:
    'Keyboard shortcut hints are small labels shaped like keys that show users which combinations trigger an action, often in tooltips, menus, or a dedicated help panel. They make power users faster and they teach beginners by example.\n\nSpell out modifier names the first time (Command, Option, Shift) before falling back to symbols, and use the platform-correct labels (Command on Mac, Control on Windows). Group shortcuts by what they do (Navigation, Editing, View) in a help panel, and offer a search field if there are more than a couple of dozen.\n\nMake sure the shortcuts themselves do not conflict with assistive tech or browser shortcuts that users depend on.',

  disclosure:
    'A disclosure is a single show-and-hide pair: a header with an arrow that toggles one block of content. It is a smaller, simpler cousin of the accordion, ideal when you only need to hide one optional thing (advanced settings, an extra paragraph).\n\nUse a real button under the hood so it is keyboard-accessible by default, mark its expanded state with aria-expanded, and animate the open and close so the change is easy to follow. If you find yourself adding a second disclosure right next to the first, switch to an accordion.\n\nIf the hidden content is long enough to be its own page, link to that page instead of hiding it inline.',

  scrollarea:
    'A scroll area is a fixed-size box that scrolls its overflowing content while the rest of the page stays in place. It is useful inside cards, panels, and modals where a section can grow but the surrounding layout should not.\n\nCustom scrollbars (thinner, themed) make it look intentional, but always keep the content reachable from the keyboard (Page Up and Page Down, Home and End) and remember that some platforms hide scrollbars until interaction, which can confuse users. Show clear top and bottom shadows or fades so people know there is more content.\n\nAvoid nested scroll areas where you can; they confuse touch gestures.',

  stickyheader:
    'A sticky header is a row of column titles that stays pinned at the top while the rest of the table scrolls. It is essential for any data table taller than one screen because the column meaning is otherwise lost.\n\nMake sure the sticky element actually sits inside a scrolling container, not the page, or it will not stick the way you expect. Pair it with a sticky first column on wide tables so labels and identifiers stay visible together.\n\nKeep the header tall enough to read, and consider a subtle shadow under it once scrolled so it visually separates from the content. On small screens, consider a different layout entirely (cards) since narrow tables get unreadable fast.',

  toolbar:
    'A toolbar is a horizontal row of grouped action buttons, often appearing above editors, tables, or canvases. Group related actions with separators (formatting, alignment, history), and use icons with tooltips for compact bars or icons with text for clarity.\n\nSupport keyboard navigation along the toolbar with Arrow keys (a single tab stop is preferred so toolbars do not steal many tab stops). For long toolbars, place rare actions in an overflow menu, and make sure focus state is visible because keyboard users will lean on the toolbar heavily.\n\nMark active states (Bold pressed) with both color and a pressed appearance so the state is not color-only.',

  cookieconsent:
    'A cookie consent banner asks visitors which optional tracking they allow and stores their answer. It is required in many regions (the European Union among them) for analytics, ads, and similar tools.\n\nBuild it as three real choices (Accept all, Reject all, and Customize) with equal visual weight, not a giant Accept button next to a hidden Reject link. Document which categories of cookies you set and what each one does.\n\nMake sure the banner does not block essential content or the page core actions, save the choice for a reasonable period, and provide a link to revisit the decision later from the footer.',

  sharesheet:
    'A share sheet is the panel you open when sharing a link, listing apps and channels (Copy link, Email, Slack, X, WhatsApp, Show QR). On mobile browsers that support it, the Web Share API hands off to the native share sheet which already knows the user installed apps; fall back to your own list when the API is unavailable.\n\nAlways offer Copy link as the most universal option with a clear confirmation, pre-fill share text where the API allows, and trap focus inside the sheet while it is open. Keep targets large enough to tap, label them clearly, and remember that not every channel supports rich previews equally.',

  presencedot:
    'A presence dot is a small colored circle on an avatar or row showing whether someone is online, away, or busy. It is common in chat apps, collaboration tools, and team directories.\n\nPair the color with another signal (a small icon, a border style, a text label on hover) because color alone leaves out color-blind users and assistive tech. Decide what each state actually means (auto-away after how many minutes, manually set busy, do-not-disturb) and make those rules visible in the user profile so people understand.\n\nKeep the dot large enough to see in dense lists, and align it consistently relative to the avatar so the eye learns where to look.',

  countdown:
    'A countdown shows the time remaining until a moment: a launch, a sale ending, a code expiring. Format it depending on scale (3 days, 4 hours; or 4:32 on a one-time code) and update gracefully without jumping the layout.\n\nFor long countdowns, do not refresh every second; the page does not need to thrash for a sale that ends next week. For accessibility, consider a polite live region update on a meaningful interval (each minute) rather than every second.\n\nOnce the countdown reaches zero, show a clear next state (Closed, Expired, Live now) so the page never sits at 0:00.',

  relativetime:
    'Relative time turns a timestamp into a friendly phrase like "2 minutes ago", "yesterday", or "in 3 days". It feels natural for activity feeds, comments, and notifications.\n\nAlways include the absolute time on hover or focus (a tooltip) so people can see the exact moment when needed. Update relative times occasionally so "just now" does not stay forever, but do not redraw constantly.\n\nLocalize the text for each language because rules vary by language and timezone (yesterday is not always one calendar day back). For long horizons (months, years), switch to absolute dates because "8 months ago" is rarely as useful as a real date.',

  qrcode:
    'A QR code encodes a small piece of text (usually a URL) into a square image you can scan with a phone camera. It is great for handing off from desktop to mobile (open this dashboard on your phone), sharing a link without typing, ticketing, and Wi-Fi setup.\n\nGenerate codes from a real library so the encoding is correct, leave a small white margin (the quiet zone) around the code so cameras can find it, and pick an error-correction level high enough for your medium (print needs more than screen). Always include the URL as plain text under the code so people without a scanner can still type it.',

  fileuploadrow:
    'A file upload row is the small horizontal record that appears for each file once it has been added to an upload. It usually shows the file name, size, a progress bar, and an action like Remove or Retry.\n\nKeep the row friendly: long file names should truncate in the middle so the extension stays visible, sizes should be in human units (KB, MB), and errors should explain how to fix them (too large, wrong type) instead of using cryptic codes. Group rows under a heading like "3 files" or "Uploading", and offer a Cancel all action when there are several.\n\nAnnounce status changes politely so screen readers track progress without interruption.',

  searchfield:
    'A search field is a dedicated input for searching the screen or the site, separate from generic text fields. Use input type="search" so browsers add the right keyboard and a clear button, and consider showing recent searches or suggestions in a dropdown as the user types.\n\nFor app-wide search, pair it with a keyboard shortcut (often slash or Command-K) and a clear placeholder that hints at what is searchable. Decide whether results filter as you type or only after Enter, and stick to one style.\n\nShow empty states clearly (no results vs no query yet), and make the field visible from anywhere people might want to search.',

  linkcard:
    'A link preview card appears when a URL is pasted in a chat, post, or comment. It shows a thumbnail image, page title, short description, and the site name, sourced from standard metadata published by the destination page (often called Open Graph tags).\n\nUse it to give people enough context to decide whether to click. Plan for missing metadata: many sites do not publish all of it, so design a fallback layout with just the host name and the URL.\n\nCache previews so you do not refetch them every render, sanitize content to avoid loading remote scripts, and respect privacy by fetching previews from your server, not the viewer browser.',

  formcolumns:
    'Multi-column form layouts place related short fields side by side on wide screens (First name and Last name on one row) and stack everything to a single column on narrow screens. They reduce vertical scrolling on long forms without confusing the eye.\n\nGroup fields that belong together with a section heading or a thin divider, keep labels above fields rather than to the side so labels never wrap awkwardly, and align field heights so the row reads cleanly. Always preserve the natural tab order: top to bottom, then left to right.\n\nOn mobile, columns should stack into a single column at a comfortable width so people can fill in the form with one thumb.',

  keyvalue:
    'A key-value list shows pairs of label and value, like a small property sheet: Status: Active, Owner: Jamie, Created: Jan 12. It is great for inspectors, settings overviews, API response previews, and order summaries.\n\nKeep label text consistent (sentence case throughout) and align values so the eye can scan quickly. For a vertical layout, labels go above values; for a horizontal one, labels sit on the left in a fixed column width.\n\nUse a clear separator color or weight so the structure is obvious in dark and light mode. For long values like long URLs, allow word-break or truncation with a copy action so the layout does not blow up.',

  treegrid:
    'A treegrid is a table whose rows can expand to reveal child rows, mixing the comparison power of a table with the hierarchy of a tree. It is great for budgets, file managers with file metadata, organizational reports, and project plans with tasks and subtasks.\n\nUse a small caret in the first column to expand and collapse, and indent child rows so the structure is visible at a glance. Keep child rows aligned with their parent columns so values stack neatly.\n\nSupport keyboard navigation (Right arrow to expand, Left arrow to collapse, Up and Down to move) and announce expanded state to screen readers using the standard treegrid roles.',

  kanban:
    'A kanban board is a row of columns that represent stages of a workflow (Backlog, In progress, Review, Done), with cards that move between columns as work progresses. It is the standard visual for project management and content pipelines.\n\nMake columns scrollable independently when they get long, label the column count visibly so it is easy to spot bottlenecks, and support drag and drop with a keyboard alternative for accessibility (a Move menu on each card). Persist column order and card position immediately after a move so refreshes do not lose work.\n\nOn small screens, switch to a single-column view that lets people scroll horizontally between stages or change stage from a select.',

  activitystream:
    'An activity stream is a chronological feed of events written in the form "User did Y to Z". Use it for audit trails, project history, and notification archives.\n\nEach entry should be one short sentence with the actor name, the action verb, and the object, plus a relative time (and the exact time on hover). Group entries by day so the feed is easy to scan, and offer simple filters (by user, by action type) on long streams.\n\nBe careful with privacy and detail level: not every event belongs in a public activity stream, especially if it leaks sensitive data. Announce new entries politely so screen readers do not get spammed.',

  filterpanel:
    'A filter panel is a sidebar or drawer of filter controls (checkboxes, ranges, selects) placed beside a list, table, or map. Use it when the result set is large and people genuinely need many filters at once.\n\nKeep the most used filters at the top and put advanced ones in a collapsible section so the panel does not become a wall of controls. Choose either instant-apply (results update as filters change) or explicit Apply (with a clearly labeled button), then be consistent.\n\nShow active filters as removable chips above the results, and add a Clear all action. Sync filter state with the URL so filtered views can be shared and bookmarked.',

  radiocards:
    'Radio cards are radio choices styled as large clickable cards with room for an icon, title, and a sentence of description. Use them when each option needs more explaining than a tiny radio circle can hold (choosing a billing plan, picking an account type, selecting an integration).\n\nThe whole card should be the click target, the selected card should be obvious with a colored border and a check mark (not color alone), and a real radio input should sit inside each card so screen readers and keyboard users get standard behavior for free. Keep card heights consistent so the row is calm, and stack to a single column on narrow screens.',

  togglebutton:
    'A toggle button stays in a pressed or released state to represent an on or off setting. The classic uses are formatting buttons in editors (Bold pressed) and view filters that turn a category on or off.\n\nIt is similar to a switch in spirit but lives in toolbars and groups, not in settings. Use the button role with aria-pressed so assistive tech announces the state, make the pressed appearance distinct from a hover, and pair color with a visual depth or check icon so the state is not color-only.\n\nFor one of several mutually exclusive options, use a segmented control instead.',

  actionsheet:
    'An action sheet is a list of choices that slides up from the bottom of the screen, common on phones for confirming actions or picking from a few options. It pairs well with destructive actions because the bottom of the screen is easy to reach and easy to cancel.\n\nAlways include a clear Cancel option at the very bottom (or as a separate dismiss area), label destructive actions with a different color and a clear verb (Delete, Remove), and trap focus inside the sheet while it is open. On larger screens, an action sheet often becomes an inline popover or a modal because there is more room and a different mouse-driven interaction model.',

  meter:
    'A meter shows a value within a known range, like disk usage, password strength, calories left, or a score. It is similar to a progress bar but represents a current measurement, not the percentage of a task.\n\nUse the HTML meter element where possible because it brings semantics for assistive tech for free. Mark the low, optimum, and high zones so people understand whether the value is good or bad, and pair color with text or icon (do not use red alone to mean "danger").\n\nFor indeterminate loading, do not use a meter; that is what a spinner is for.',

  banner:
    'A banner is a full-width notice placed below the page header, used for system-wide messages: maintenance windows, free trial expiring, payment failed, important announcements. Pick a color that matches severity (info, warning, error) and pair it with an icon, a short headline, and one clear action where appropriate (Update now, Learn more).\n\nMake the banner dismissible when the message is informational, and persistent for messages that block the user from succeeding. Avoid stacking multiple banners; if you have several messages at once, group them and prioritize.\n\nUse a polite live region for non-urgent banners and an assertive one for blocking errors.',

  hovercard:
    'A hover card is a richer version of a tooltip: a small floating panel that appears on hover or focus and contains structured content like a user mini-profile, a link preview, or a definition. Because keyboard users and touch users do not hover, always give them another way to open it (focus a link, tap a small info icon, click the trigger).\n\nKeep the panel readable and not too tall, support tabbing through links inside, and dismiss it cleanly on outside click and Escape. The line between hover card and popover is fuzzy; if the content needs frequent interaction (forms, filters), prefer a popover, which opens on a real click.',

  producttour:
    'A product tour walks new users through a feature with a series of small popover steps that point at parts of the interface. It can shorten the path to "first success", but if it is too long it just becomes another hurdle to dismiss.\n\nKeep tours short (three to five steps), let users skip and resume, point at real elements rather than vague areas of the screen, and make sure the underlying UI is still functional during the tour. Save progress so people who close it can finish later.\n\nEmpty states and inline hints often teach better than a tour because they appear in context, exactly when relevant.',

  loadingoverlay:
    'A loading overlay is a translucent layer with a spinner and label that covers a section or the whole page while a critical action is in flight (signing in, saving, generating a report). Use it sparingly because it blocks all interaction.\n\nAlways include a clear short message telling users what is happening, and a way to cancel for any operation that might take more than a few seconds. Trap focus on the overlay while it is open, lock background scroll, and avoid flashing the overlay for very fast actions (introduce a small delay so very quick responses do not show it at all).\n\nRestore focus to a sensible element when the overlay is removed.',
};
